##               1  2  3
##   setosa     33 17  0
##   versicolor  0  4 46
##   virginica   0  0 50
extended_points <- cbind(kmeans.result$centers[,c("Sepal.Length", "Sepal.Width")], seq_along(kmeans.result$centers[,1]))
colnames(extended_points)[3] <- "colour"
add_points <- function(item) {
  geom_point(data = NULL, aes_string(x = item[1], y = item[2]), col = item[3], size = 5, shape = 8)
}
center_points <- apply(extended_points, 1, add_points)

pltbase <- ggplot(iris2, aes(Sepal.Length, Sepal.Width)) + geom_point(col = kmeans.result$cluster)
for(p in center_points){
  pltbase <- pltbase + p
}
pltbase

idx <- sample(1:nrow(iris), 40)
irisSample <- iris[idx,]
irisSample$Species <- NULL
hc <- hclust(dist(irisSample), method="ave")
plot(hc, hang = -1, labels=iris$Species[idx])
rect.hclust(hc, k=3)

groups <- cutree(hc, k=3)

The idea of density-based clustering is to group objects into one cluster if they are connected to one another by densely populated area. \(\alpha\) MinPts \(\alpha\) \(\alpha\) density-reachable \(\alpha\) 

library(fpc)
iris2 <- iris[-5]
ds <- dbscan(iris2, eps=0.42, MinPts=5)
table(ds$cluster, iris$Species) # 0
##    
##     setosa versicolor virginica
##   0      2         10        17
##   1     48          0         0
##   2      0         37         0
##   3      0          3        33
plot(ds, iris2)

plot(ds, iris2[c(1,4)])

plotcluster(iris2, ds$cluster)

set.seed(435)
idx <- sample(1:nrow(iris), 10)
newData <- iris[idx,-5]
newData <- newData + matrix(runif(10*4, min=0, max=0.2), nrow=10, ncol=4)
myPred <- predict(ds, iris2, newData)
plot(iris2[c(1,4)], col=1+ds$cluster)
points(newData[c(1,4)], pch="*", col=1+myPred, cex=3)

table(myPred, iris$Species[idx])
##       
## myPred setosa versicolor virginica
##      0      0          0         1
##      1      3          0         0
